ion, one that they creatively adapted, often against stiff resistance. Enriching these texts with short but insightful essays that contextualize their importance, the editors offer an accessible portrait of the early research university, one that provides invaluable insights not only into the historical development of higher learning but also its role in modern society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEducation, HigherxAims and objectives. 0aEducation, HigherzGermanyxPhilosophy. 0aEducation, HigherzUnited StatesxGerman influences. 0aEducation, HigherzUnited StatesxPhilosophy. 0aUniversities and collegesxHistoryy19th centuryvSources. 0aUniversities and collegeszGermanyxHistoryy19th centuryvSources. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th centuryvSources. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aBaldwin, Charles Sears, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBancroft, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoss, John J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEliot, Charles William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEly, Richard Theodore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFichte, J. G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGedike, Friedrich, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGideonse, Harry D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilman, Daniel Coit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, G. Stanley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarper, William Rainey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, James M., econtributor.4ctb